snippet.textDisplay: thailand and vietnam have more distinctive and preserved food culture and traditions compared to cambodia.. Khmer food culture is more mixed with thai, vietnamese, chinese and french food influences and some/alot of traditions were lost during the genocide in the name of the arsehole.. khmer breakfast is mixed apart from roast meat with rice (there's kuy teav, soup/dry with bone soup, in some restaurant options include dim sum, beef ragout with baguette on side, french style breakfast and chinese style breakfast is uncommon e.g porridge, you tiao & soya milk),, similar thing for thai breakfast as well.. but more used to having french, chinese style breakfast and/or kopi, eggs and kaya toast on side.. depending on the availability,, i find japanese breakfast very satisfying but find spaghetti and bread toast/slice in japan odd since the japanese kitchen staff use that to feed the GI joes back then

snippet.textDisplay:
The traditional Amok way is steamed. But, in the modern day era, people could get creative with their own ways of cooking Amok.


* i don't know about the first Amok you tried, honestly, it does not look that appealing-to-eat to me. (cuz probably, as Cambodian, i would not have my Amok cooked like that, maybe)
* that second Amok you tried in Rom-deng restaurant, it's one of ways to cook Amok. i've been there once, tried it, yes, it's one of the best Amok in Phnom Penh, but i don't really recommend it tho cuz it could be pricey.(with around 6-8$ price, i could find better Amok and it's less expensive)
